===============================================================
[2026-03-02] DECISION #1: Multi-stage Dockerfile
===============================================================

## Options Considered
1. Separate Dockerfiles for app, celery-worker, celery-beat
2. Single multi-stage Dockerfile with targets

## Choice
Option 2 — single Dockerfile with targets

## Rationale
Reduces duplication. All services share the same base image and deps.
Docker Compose `target` directive selects the appropriate stage.

## Impact
docker-compose.yml uses `target: app`, `target: celery-worker`, `target: celery-beat`

---------------------------------------------------------------

===============================================================
[2026-03-03] DECISION #2: Reject 6 Proposed Platform Gaps
===============================================================

## Options Considered
1. Implement all 6 proposed gaps (BUP patches, OpenClaw SDK, capabilities
   registry, webhook registry, coalition mode, argument graph endpoint)
2. Implement only items with partial validity (#3 capabilities, #6 graph)
3. Reject all 6 as non-gaps; defer #3 and #6 as post-MVP feature requests

## Choice
Option 3 — reject all 6; defer #3 and #6 to post-MVP backlog

## Rationale
- Items 1, 2, 5 conflate OpenClaw's internal architecture with platform
  concerns. Spec Section 2 explicitly states agents are black boxes.
- Item 4 contradicts design.md Section 4.4 which deliberately chose REST
  polling over webhooks for agent communication.
- Items 3, 6 are valid feature requests but not gaps in spec implementation.
  Existing fields (model_info, GraphNode.source_debate_id) already provide
  the underlying data; dedicated endpoints would be UX improvements.
- Zero code changes needed. Zero regressions possible.

## Impact
- No code modified
- Post-MVP backlog updated with items #3 (capabilities registry) and
  #6 (debate-scoped argument graph endpoint) as optional enhancements

